---

<SpecLayout
  title="Route Spec — Substack → Astro · Portage"
  description="Portage route specification: migrating a Substack newsletter to Astro. ZIP export parsing, CSV + HTML correlation, CDN image download, mention conversion, subscribe-button removal, and CLI."
  origin="Substack"
  status="beta"
  lede="A crossing for the Substack writer who wants to own their own site: posts, pages, podcasts, and threads from a ZIP export mapped to Astro content collections. The export is text-only — images live on Substack's CDN and must be downloaded while the publication is still live."
  meta={meta}
  toc={toc}
>
  <section class="spec-sec" id="s01">
    <h2><span class="num">01</span>Overview</h2>
    <p>This route carries a Substack newsletter into an Astro project as <strong>content collections</strong> backed by Markdown or MDX files. The source is Substack's <strong>ZIP export</strong> — a single downloadable archive containing a CSV of post metadata and a directory of HTML body files.</p>
    <p>Substack's export is deliberately narrow: it carries post text and metadata, but <strong>no images, no subscriber data, and no theme</strong>. All images are served from <code>substackcdn.com</code> and must be downloaded separately while the publication is live. This is the same constraint the Squarespace route faces with CDN-hosted assets, and Portage handles it the same way.</p>
    <div class="note keep">
      <span class="lbl">Moves intact</span>
      <p>Published posts, pages, podcast episodes, thread posts, subtitles, canonical URLs, publish dates, audience visibility, and inline image references (downloaded and rehosted).</p>
    </div>
    <div class="note warn">
      <span class="lbl">Time-sensitive</span>
      <p>Image download requires the Substack publication to still be live. Once a publication is deleted, <code>substackcdn.com</code> image links break permanently. Run the migration <strong>before</strong> decommissioning the source publication.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="spec-sec" id="s02">
    <h2><span class="num">02</span>Extraction</h2>
    <p>Substack generates the export from <code>Settings → Exports → Create new export</code>. The download is a ZIP file with a known structure. Portage unzips it, reads the CSV for metadata, reads each HTML file for body content, and joins them by <code>post_id</code>.</p>
    <h3>A · ZIP structure</h3>
    <div class="code">
      <div class="code-bar"><span class="name">substack export zip</span><span class="meta">tree</span></div>
      <pre is:raw>substack-export.zip
├── posts.csv                 <span class="c">← metadata for every post</span>
└── posts/                    <span class="c">← one HTML file per post</span>
    ├── 12345.leaving-the-walled-garden.html
    ├── 67890.harbor-notes.html
    └── <span class="c">…</span></pre>
    </div>
    <h3>B · CSV fields</h3>
    <p>The <code>posts.csv</code> file contains one row per post with the following columns:</p>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>CSV column</th><th>Type</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">post_id</span></td><td><span class="ty">string</span></td><td>Numeric prefix of the HTML filename. Used to correlate CSV row with <code>posts/{post_id}.{slug}.html</code>.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">title</span></td><td><span class="ty">string</span></td><td>Post title. May contain special characters that need escaping for YAML frontmatter.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">subtitle</span></td><td><span class="ty">string</span></td><td>Subtitle / description. HTML-decoded before mapping.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">url</span></td><td><span class="ty">url</span></td><td>Canonical Substack URL (<code>https://pub.substack.com/p/slug</code>). Used for redirect generation.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">post_date</span></td><td><span class="ty">date</span></td><td>Publish date. Used for <code>pubDate</code>, <code>createdAt</code>, and <code>updatedAt</code>.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">is_published</span></td><td><span class="ty">string</span></td><td><code>"true"</code> or <code>"false"</code>. Maps to draft status.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">audience</span></td><td><span class="ty">string</span></td><td>Access level: <code>only_paid</code>, <code>only_free</code>, or absent (public).</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">type</span></td><td><span class="ty">string</span></td><td>Content type: <code>newsletter</code>, <code>page</code>, <code>podcast</code>, <code>thread</code>. Determines target collection.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">audio_url</span></td><td><span class="ty">url</span></td><td>Podcast audio file URL (podcast type only).</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">podcast_duration</span></td><td><span class="ty">number</span></td><td>Duration in seconds (podcast type only).</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">podcast_url</span></td><td><span class="ty">url</span></td><td>Podcast episode URL (podcast type only).</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <h3>C · HTML body files</h3>
    <p>Each file in <code>posts/</code> is named <code>{post_id}.{slug}.html</code> and contains the full post body as rendered HTML. The slug in the filename is the canonical Substack slug. Portage reads every <code>.html</code> file in <code>posts/</code> and matches it to the CSV row by <code>post_id</code>.</p>
    <div class="code">
      <div class="code-bar"><span class="name">extract · zip</span><span class="meta">bash</span></div>
      <pre is:raw><span class="pr">$</span> npx portage extract <span class="fl">--from</span> substack \
    <span class="fl">--export</span> ./substack-export.zip <span class="fl">--to</span> ./astro-project
<span class="out">→ 84 posts · 3 pages · 2 podcasts · 5 threads · 142 images referenced</span></pre>
    </div>
    <h3>D · Crawl fallback</h3>
    <p>The ZIP export carries no SEO metadata, no <code>og:image</code>, and no author profile data. An optional <code>--crawl</code> flag supplements the ZIP by scraping the live publication's pages for structured data (<code>og:title</code>, <code>og:description</code>, <code>og:image</code>, <code>ld+json</code> author info).</p>
    <div class="code">
      <div class="code-bar"><span class="name">extract · zip + crawl</span><span class="meta">bash</span></div>
      <pre is:raw><span class="pr">$</span> npx portage extract <span class="fl">--from</span> substack <span class="fl">--export</span> ./export.zip \
    <span class="fl">--url</span> https://my-pub.substack.com <span class="fl">--crawl</span> <span class="fl">--to</span> ./astro-project</pre>
    </div>
    <div class="note">
      <span class="lbl">Note</span>
      <p>The CSV does not carry body content — only metadata. The HTML files are the sole source of post bodies. If a CSV row has no matching HTML file, the post is listed as a gap in the manifest and skipped. (The Ghost migrator applies the same rule: "Only process Substack posts where its corresponding HTML file exists.")</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="spec-sec" id="s03">
    <h2><span class="num">03</span>Content mapping</h2>
    <p>Each Substack post becomes one Markdown/MDX file. Content types split into separate collections by the <code>type</code> field.</p>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Substack field</th><th>Type</th><th></th><th>Astro frontmatter</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">title</span></td><td><span class="ty">string</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">title</span></td><td>Required. HTML-decoded, YAML-escaped.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">subtitle</span></td><td><span class="ty">string</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">description</span></td><td>HTML-decoded. Falls back to generated excerpt.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">(filename slug)</span></td><td><span class="ty">string</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">(filename)</span></td><td>Extracted from HTML filename: <code>{post_id}.{slug}.html</code> → <code>{slug}.md</code>.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">(html body)</span></td><td><span class="ty">html</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">(body)</span></td><td>Converted to Markdown/MDX — see §04.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">post_date</span></td><td><span class="ty">date</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">pubDate</span></td><td>ISO 8601, coerced by zod.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">is_published</span></td><td><span class="ty">string</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">draft</span></td><td><code>"false"</code> → <code>draft: true</code>.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">audience</span></td><td><span class="ty">enum</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">access</span></td><td><code>only_paid</code> → <code>paid</code>; <code>only_free</code> → <code>members</code>; absent → <code>public</code>.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">type</span></td><td><span class="ty">enum</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">(collection)</span></td><td><code>newsletter</code> → blog; <code>page</code> → pages; <code>podcast</code> → podcast; <code>thread</code> → threads.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">url</span></td><td><span class="ty">url</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">canonicalURL</span></td><td>Preserves the original Substack URL as the canonical.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">audio_url</span></td><td><span class="ty">url</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">audioUrl</span></td><td>Podcast episodes only. Downloaded and rehosted if <code>--podcast-audio download</code>.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">podcast_duration</span></td><td><span class="ty">number</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">audioDuration</span></td><td>Seconds. Podcast episodes only.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">(og:image via crawl)</span></td><td><span class="ty">url</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">heroImage</span></td><td>Only when <code>--crawl</code> is on. Falls back to first inline image.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <h3>Content type → collection mapping</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Substack type</th><th>Astro collection</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">newsletter</span></td><td><span class="af">blog</span></td><td>Standard posts. Default content type.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">page</span></td><td><span class="af">pages</span></td><td>Static pages (About, FAQ, etc.).</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">podcast</span></td><td><span class="af">podcast</span></td><td>Audio episodes. Includes <code>audioUrl</code> and <code>audioDuration</code> fields.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">thread</span></td><td><span class="af">threads</span></td><td>Discussion threads. Body may contain reply-chain HTML.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="spec-sec" id="s04">
    <h2><span class="num">04</span>Content transforms</h2>
    <p>Substack stores body content as <strong>rendered HTML</strong> — no structured AST like Ghost's Lexical or Mobiledoc. This is simpler to parse than a custom AST but requires cleanup of Substack-specific markup. Portage uses <code>turndown</code> for the HTML-to-Markdown conversion (same library as the Squarespace route) and applies Substack-specific transforms before and after.</p>
    <h3>A · Pre-turndown cleanup</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Substack markup</th><th></th><th>Transform</th><th>Notes</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">&lt;span class="mention-wrap"&gt;</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><code>@{name}</code> text</td><td>Extract <code>name</code> from <code>data-attrs</code> JSON. Render as plain text with <code>@</code> prefix.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">Subscribe buttons</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td>Removed</td><td><code>&lt;div class="subscribe-widget"&gt;</code> and inline subscribe CTA links stripped. Optional replacement link via <code>--subscribe-link</code>.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">Comment links</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td>Rewritten or removed</td><td><code>/comments</code> anchors rewritten to <code>--comment-link</code> value, or removed with <code>--no-comments</code>.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">Inline styles</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td>Stripped</td><td>Substack injects <code>style</code> attributes for font, color, and margin. These are stripped to leave semantic markup.</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">Substack embeds</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td>Link fallback</td><td>Embedded Substack posts or other Substack content rendered as plain links to the original URL.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <h3>B · Post-turndown transforms</h3>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Pattern</th><th></th><th>Output (Markdown)</th><th>Output (MDX)</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">Image + caption</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><code>![alt](local-path)</code> + italic caption</td><td><span class="af">&lt;Figure&gt;</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">YouTube / Vimeo embed</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td>Link fallback</td><td><span class="af">&lt;Embed&gt;</span></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">Code block</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td>Fenced block with language</td><td>Fenced block</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">Blockquote</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td>Blockquote</td><td>Blockquote</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">Button / CTA link</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td>Markdown link</td><td><span class="af">&lt;Button&gt;</span></td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <div class="note">
      <span class="lbl">HTML vs. structured content</span>
      <p>Substack's HTML is simpler to parse than Ghost's Lexical or Mobiledoc AST, but it carries more presentation residue (inline styles, Substack-specific class names, proprietary mention spans). The pre-turndown cleanup step strips this residue before conversion, producing cleaner Markdown than a naive HTML-to-Markdown pass would.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="spec-sec" id="s05">
    <h2><span class="num">05</span>Assets</h2>
    <p>Substack's export contains <strong>no image or media files</strong>. All images are served from <code>substackcdn.com</code>, backed by S3 at <code>substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com</code>. Portage downloads every referenced image and rewrites the path to a local file.</p>
    <h3>A · Image URL patterns</h3>
    <div class="code">
      <div class="code-bar"><span class="name">substackcdn url patterns</span><span class="meta">url</span></div>
      <pre is:raw"><span class="c"># CDN proxy with resize parameters</span>
https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/{params}/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F{uuid}_{size}.ext

<span class="c"># Direct S3 URL</span>
https://substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com/public/images/{uuid}_{size}.ext</pre>
    </div>
    <h3>B · Download pipeline</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Fetch originals</strong> — strip resize parameters; request the full-resolution source image. Astro regenerates responsive sizes via its own image pipeline.</li>
      <li><strong>Download &amp; dedupe</strong> — each unique image is fetched once and content-hashed; duplicates collapse to a single file.</li>
      <li><strong>Rewrite references</strong> — inline <code>&lt;img&gt;</code> <code>src</code> attributes and hero images point at local paths after download.</li>
      <li><strong>External images</strong> — images not hosted on <code>substackcdn.com</code> or <code>substack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com</code> stay remote unless <code>--images localize-external</code>.</li>
    </ul>
    <h3>C · Podcast audio</h3>
    <p>Podcast episodes reference audio files via <code>audio_url</code>. By default these are left as remote URLs. Use <code>--podcast-audio download</code> to fetch and rehost them in <code>public/audio/</code>.</p>
    <div class="note warn">
      <span class="lbl">Images are time-sensitive</span>
      <p>Substack CDN images are only accessible while the publication exists. If the publication is deleted, all image links break permanently. This is the same constraint the Squarespace route faces with CDN images. Portage warns if the publication URL is unreachable or returns 404 for image requests.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="note">
      <span class="lbl">Placement</span>
      <p><code>--images assets</code> (default) writes to <code>src/assets/blog/</code> for full Astro optimization. <code>--images public</code> writes stable URLs to <code>public/images/</code>.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="spec-sec" id="s06">
    <h2><span class="num">06</span>Routes &amp; redirects</h2>
    <p>Substack namespaces all posts under <code>/p/{slug}</code>. Astro prefers flat slugs at <code>/{slug}/</code>. Portage generates a redirect map for every post so existing links continue to work.</p>
    <div class="table-wrap">
      <table>
        <thead><tr><th>Substack route</th><th></th><th>Astro route</th><th>Handled by</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">/p/&lcub;slug&rcub;</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">/blog/&lcub;slug&rcub;/</span></td><td>Blog collection + redirect from <code>/p/{slug}</code></td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">/&lcub;page-slug&rcub;</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">/&lcub;page-slug&rcub;/</span></td><td>Pages collection</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">/podcast/&lcub;slug&rcub;</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">/podcast/&lcub;slug&rcub;/</span></td><td>Podcast collection</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">/subscribe</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">--subscribe-link value</span></td><td>Configurable destination</td></tr>
          <tr><td><span class="gf">/feed</span></td><td class="arrowcell">→</td><td><span class="af">/rss.xml</span></td><td><code>@astrojs/rss</code> + redirect</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>/p/ prefix redirect</strong> — every Substack post URL includes <code>/p/</code>. Portage generates a redirect from <code>/p/{slug}</code> to <code>/blog/{slug}/</code> (or <code>/{slug}/</code> with <code>--route-base /</code>) so inbound links survive the crossing.</li>
      <li><strong>Trailing slashes</strong> — Substack does not use them; Astro can. Portage sets <code>trailingSlash: 'always'</code> and generates redirects from the non-trailing-slash Substack URLs.</li>
      <li><strong>Redirect map</strong> — emitted as <code>_redirects</code> (Netlify), <code>vercel.json</code>, or Astro <code>redirects</code> config via <code>--redirects</code>.</li>
      <li><strong>Sitemap</strong> — <code>@astrojs/sitemap</code> added and configured to the new base URL.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="note">
      <span class="lbl">Ghost's redirect pattern</span>
      <p>Ghost's built-in Substack migrator uses the regex <code>\/p\/(?![0-9a-fA-F]{8}-...)(.*)</code> to redirect <code>/p/{slug}</code> to <code>/{slug}</code> while excluding UUID-style preview URLs. Portage applies the same pattern.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="spec-sec" id="s07">
    <h2><span class="num">07</span>Out of scope</h2>
    <p>Portage moves <strong>content</strong>. Substack is also a subscription, payment, and community platform, and those systems do not have a one-to-one home in a static Astro site. The following are deliberately not migrated.</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Subscribers &amp; members</strong> — exported separately as CSV by Substack. Auth, sign-up, and gating are yours to rebuild.</li>
      <li><strong>Paid tiers &amp; Stripe</strong> — billing relationships cannot be carried; reconnect at your new provider.</li>
      <li><strong>Community / Chat</strong> — Substack's discussion and chat features are not in the export.</li>
      <li><strong>Comments</strong> — not included in the export. Use a third-party system (e.g. Giscus) if needed.</li>
      <li><strong>Theme &amp; design</strong> — Substack's layout and styling are not transferable. You rebuild presentation in Astro.</li>
      <li><strong>Email analytics</strong> — per-post <code>.delivers.csv</code> and <code>.opens.csv</code> files in the export are delivery metrics, not content. They are not migrated.</li>
      <li><strong>Recommendations</strong> — Substack's publication recommendation feature has no Astro equivalent.</li>
      <li><strong>Notes</strong> — Substack Notes are not part of the export.</li>
    </ul>
    <div class="note warn">
      <span class="lbl">Paid-only content</span>
      <p>Posts with <code>audience: only_paid</code> are extracted and written with <code>access: paid</code> and <code>draft: true</code> by default, so they never publish unintentionally. Decide your gating strategy, then flip them on deliberately.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="spec-sec" id="s08">
    <h2><span class="num">08</span>Edge cases</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>CSV row with no HTML file</strong> — if a <code>post_id</code> appears in the CSV but has no matching file in <code>posts/</code>, the post is listed as a gap in the manifest and skipped. This happens with certain draft or deleted posts.</li>
      <li><strong>HTML file with no CSV row</strong> — if an HTML file exists in <code>posts/</code> but has no matching CSV row, the post is processed using filename-derived metadata only (slug from filename, date from file modification time). Warned in the manifest.</li>
      <li><strong>Mention spans</strong> — <code>&lt;span class="mention-wrap" data-attrs="{...}"&gt;</code> elements are Substack-proprietary. Portage extracts the <code>name</code> field from the JSON and renders as <code>@Name</code> text. If the JSON is malformed, the span is stripped and a warning is logged.</li>
      <li><strong>Subscribe buttons in body</strong> — Substack injects subscribe CTA widgets mid-content. These are stripped by default. Use <code>--subscribe-link</code> to replace them with a link to your own signup page.</li>
      <li><strong>Special characters in titles</strong> — colons, quotes, and other YAML-significant characters in <code>title</code> must be escaped for frontmatter. Portage wraps titles in double quotes and escapes internal quotes.</li>
      <li><strong>Drafts</strong> — included only with <code>--include-drafts</code>. Draft posts carry <code>draft: true</code> and may lack a <code>post_date</code> (Portage falls back to file modification time).</li>
      <li><strong>Podcast episodes without audio</strong> — if <code>audio_url</code> is empty or the URL returns 404, the episode is still written with <code>audioUrl</code> set to the broken URL and a warning logged. You can re-link the audio later.</li>
      <li><strong>Thread reply chains</strong> — thread-type posts may contain nested reply HTML. Portage carries the HTML as-is; reply formatting may need manual cleanup.</li>
      <li><strong>Slug collisions</strong> — a post and a page sharing a slug are namespaced by collection; conflicts are reported in the manifest.</li>
      <li><strong>Image 404s</strong> — if a <code>substackcdn.com</code> image URL returns 404 (publication deleted, image removed), the reference is preserved as the original remote URL and a warning logged. Portage does not fail the entire migration for one broken image.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <section class="spec-sec" id="s09">
    <h2><span class="num">09</span>Output</h2>
    <p>A predictable, buildable Astro project. The manifest at the root is the full ledger of what was extracted, transformed, and written.</p>
    <div class="code">
      <div class="code-bar"><span class="name">project tree</span><span class="meta">output</span></div>
      <pre is:raw>astro-project/
├── src/
│   ├── content/
│   │   ├── blog/              <span class="c">← 84 posts (newsletter type)</span>
│   │   ├── pages/             <span class="c">← 3 pages</span>
│   │   ├── podcast/           <span class="c">← 2 podcast episodes</span>
│   │   └── threads/           <span class="c">← 5 threads</span>
│   ├── assets/blog/           <span class="c">← 142 localized images</span>
│   ├── components/portage/    <span class="c">← MDX stubs (if --content mdx)</span>
│   └── content.config.ts
├── public/
│   ├── _redirects             <span class="c">← 84 /p/{slug} → /blog/{slug}/ redirects</span>
│   └── audio/                 <span class="c">← podcast audio files (if --podcast-audio download)</span>
├── portage.manifest.json      <span class="c">← extract / transform / load ledger</span>
└── astro.config.mjs           <span class="c">← trailingSlash · sitemap · redirects</span></pre>
    </div>
    <h3>Content collection schema</h3>
    <div class="code">
      <div class="code-bar"><span class="name">src/content.config.ts</span><span class="meta">typescript</span></div>
      <pre is:raw><span class="k">import</span> { defineCollection, z } <span class="k">from</span> <span class="s">'astro:content'</span>;
<span class="k">import</span> { glob } <span class="k">from</span> <span class="s">'astro/loaders'</span>;

<span class="k">const</span> blog = defineCollection({
  loader: glob({ pattern: <span class="s">'**/*.{md,mdx}'</span>, base: <span class="s">'./src/content/blog'</span> }),
  schema: ({ image }) => z.object({
    title: z.string(),
    description: z.string().optional(),
    pubDate: z.coerce.date(),
    heroImage: image().optional(),
    draft: z.boolean().default(false),
    access: z.enum([<span class="s">'public'</span>, <span class="s">'members'</span>, <span class="s">'paid'</span>]).default(<span class="s">'public'</span>),
    canonicalURL: z.string().url().optional(),
  }),
});

<span class="k">const</span> pages = defineCollection({
  loader: glob({ pattern: <span class="s">'**/*.{md,mdx}'</span>, base: <span class="s">'./src/content/pages'</span> }),
  schema: ({ image }) => z.object({
    title: z.string(),
    description: z.string().optional(),
    heroImage: image().optional(),
    draft: z.boolean().default(false),
  }),
});

<span class="k">const</span> podcast = defineCollection({
  loader: glob({ pattern: <span class="s">'**/*.{md,mdx}'</span>, base: <span class="s">'./src/content/podcast'</span> }),
  schema: ({ image }) => z.object({
    title: z.string(),
    description: z.string().optional(),
    pubDate: z.coerce.date(),
    heroImage: image().optional(),
    audioUrl: z.string().url().optional(),
    audioDuration: z.number().optional(),
    draft: z.boolean().default(false),
  }),
});

<span class="k">const</span> threads = defineCollection({
  loader: glob({ pattern: <span class="s">'**/*.{md,mdx}'</span>, base: <span class="s">'./src/content/threads'</span> }),
  schema: z.object({
    title: z.string(),
    pubDate: z.coerce.date(),
    draft: z.boolean().default(false),
  }),
});

<span class="k">export const</span> collections = { blog, pages, podcast, threads };</pre>
    </div>
